<section xml:id="sec_sum_proofs">
  <title>Proofs of Explicit Formulas for Sums and Products</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      We have observed patterns and conjectured explicit formulas for sums and products in <xref ref="sec_sum_conj"></xref>,
      including sums involving Fibonacci numbers,
      and in <xref ref="sec_arith_triangle"></xref>,
      including sums involving binomial coefficients.
      In a few special cases,
      we saw how to use the Binomial Theorem to prove summation formulas,
      but how do we prove the Binomial Theorem itself as well as other formulas?
      In this section, we look at two proof techniques,
      including new special cases of mathematical induction and an extension of combinatorial proofs to summations.
      We close by looking at special sums,
      such as the handshake formula from <xref ref="thm_hs"></xref> and finite geometric sums.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_sum_proofs_induction">
    <title>\subpffsumproofsind</title>
    <p>
      We can use mathematical induction to prove explicit formulas for summations and products.
      We begin with the proof format for a summation.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Given the explicitly-defined sequence <m>a_k</m> for <m>k \ge s</m>,
      prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^na_k=</m>
      (explicit rule)
      for <m>n \ge s</m>.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Write <m>f(n) =</m>(explicit rule).
        Induct on <m>n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, when <m>n=s</m> we know that
        <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^sa_k=a_s= \cdots</m> and also <m>f(s)=</m>
        (evaluate and simplify to get the same answer).
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, assume <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^{n-1}a_k=f(n-1)=</m>
        (evaluate and simplify),
        for some integer <m>n > s</m>.
        Then
        <me>
          \sum_{k=s}^na_k = \left(\sum_{k=s}^{n-1}a_k\right) + a_n = f(n-1) + a_n = \cdots \text{ (use algebra) }  \cdots = f(n)
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      The key first step in the last line of the proof uses the recursive definitions of partial sums,
      <xref ref="rem_rec_def_partial_sum"></xref>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Similarly, here is the proof format for a product.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Given the explicitly-defined sequence <m>a_k</m> for <m>k \ge s</m>,
      prove that <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=s}^na_k=</m>
      (explicit rule)
      for <m>n \ge s</m>.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Write <m>f(n) =</m>(explicit rule).
        Induct on <m>n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, when <m>n=s</m> we know that
        <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=s}^sa_k=a_s= \cdots</m> and also <m>f(s)=</m>
        (evaluate and simplify to get the same answer).
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, assume <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=s}^{n-1}a_k=f(n-1)=</m>
        (evaluate and simplify),
        for some integer <m>n > s</m>.
        Then
        <me>
          \prod_{k=s}^na_k = \left(\prod_{k=s}^{n-1}a_k\right) \cdot a_n = f(n-1) \cdot a_n = \cdots \text{ (use algebra) }  \cdots = f(n)
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      The key first step in the last line of the proof uses the recursive definitions of partial products,
      <xref ref="rem_rec_def_partial_prod"></xref>.
    </p>
    <p>
      As usual, when we introduce a new proof format,
      we give you examples to copy and edit.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_math_ind_sum_prod_formulas">
      <title>Proving sum and product formulas using mathematical induction</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_proof_ind_sum_powers2">
            <p>
              Copy the following proof.
              Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n2^k=2^{n+1}-1</m> for <m>n \ge 0</m>.
              <blockquote>
                <em>Proof</em> Write <m>f(n) = 2^{n+1}-1</m>.  Induct on <m>n</m>.  First, when <m>n=0</m> we know that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^02^k=2^0=1</m> and also <m>f(0)=2^{0+1}-1=2-1=1</m>.  Next, assume <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{n-1}2^k=f(n-1)= 2^{(n-1)+1}-1=2^n-1</m> for some integer <m>n > s</m>. Then
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=0}^n2^k \amp  = \left(\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}2^k\right) + 2^n = f(n-1) + 2^n = \left(2^n-1\right)+2^n</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp  = 2^n+2^n-1=2\cdot2^n-1=2^{n+1}-1 = f(n)</mrow>
                </md>.
              </blockquote>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_proof_ind_sum_powers2"/> to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n2 \cdot 3^k = 3^{n+1}-1</m> for <m>n\ge 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_proof_ind_prod_recip">
            <p>
              Copy the following proof.
              Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^nk=n!</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
              <blockquote>
                <em>Proof</em> Write <m>f(n) = n!</m>.  Induct on <m>n</m>.  First, when <m>n=1</m> we know that <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^1k=1=1</m> and also <m>f(1)=1!=1</m>.  Next, assume <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^{n-1}k=f(n-1)= (n-1)!</m> for some integer <m>n > s</m>. Then
                <me>
                  \prod_{k=1}^nk = \left(\prod_{k=1}^{n-1}k\right) \cdot n = f(n-1) \cdot n = \left((n-1)!\right) \cdot n = n(n-1)! =n! = f(n)
                </me>.
              </blockquote>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_proof_ind_prod_recip"/> to prove that <m>\displaystyle \prod_{j=1}^n \frac{1}{j} = \frac{1}{n!}</m> for <m>n\ge1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_proof_ind_sum_Fib_evens">
            <p>
              Copy the following proof.
              Use mathematical induction to prove that
              <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nF_{2k}=F_{2n+1}-1</m>  for <m>n \ge 1</m> where,
              as usual,
              the Fibonacci numbers are defined by <m>F_0=0</m>, <m>F_1=1</m>,
              and <m>F_n=F_{n-1} + F_{n-2}</m> for <m>n \ge 2</m>.
              <blockquote>
                <em>Proof</em> Write <m>f(n) = F_{2n+1}-1</m>.  Induct on <m>n</m>.  First, when <m>n=1</m> we have <m>\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^1F_{2k}=F_{2(1)}=F_2=1</m> and also
                <me>
                  f(1) = F_{2(1)+1}-1=F_3-1=2-1=1
                </me>.
                Next, assume
                <me>
                  \sum_{k=1}^{n-1}F_{2k} = f(n-1) = F_{2(n-1)+1}-1 = F_{2n-1}-1
                </me>
                for some integer <m>n > 1</m>. Then
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^nF_{2k} \amp  = \left( \sum_{k=1}^{n-1}F_{2k} \right) + F_{2n} = f(n-1) + F_{2n} = \left(F_{2n-1}-1\right)+F_{2n}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp  = \left(F_{2n} + F_{2n-1}\right) -1 = F_{2n+1}-1 = f(n)</mrow>
                </md>
                The next-to-last equality uses the recursive definition the Fibonacci numbers to conclude that the sum of the consecutive terms <m>F_{2n}</m> and <m>F_{2n-1}</m> equals the next term, <m>F_{2n+1}</m>.
              </blockquote>
              Note: We saw this summation in <xref ref="act_fib_sums_conj"></xref>
              <xref ref="part_fib_sums_even_index"/> and <xref ref="exam_fib_sum_conj_even_index"></xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof from <xref ref="part_proof_ind_sum_Fib_evens"/> to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{n}F_{2k-1} = F_{2n}</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
              Note: We saw this summation in <xref ref="sec_sum_conj"></xref>
              <xref ref="exer_fib_sum_odd_terms_conj"></xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_comb_sums">
    <title>\subpffcombsums</title>
    <p>
      We can use mathematical induction to prove the explicit formula of a sum of the form <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^na_k=f(n)</m>,
      but the recursive step of these proofs is based on the fact that the terms <m>a_k</m> do not depend on the upper limit <m>n</m>.
      How can we prove an explicit formula for a summation where the terms depend on <m>n</m>?
      For example, in <xref ref="sec_arith_triangle"></xref>
      we saw sums with binomial coefficients where the terms involved <m>n</m>.
      An option is to extend the proof format for a combinatorial proof,
      <xref ref="pff_comb_proof"></xref>, to apply to sums.
      This extended proof format is especially useful for proofs involving binomial coefficients, since,
      by definition, they count objects.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Given the explicitly-defined sequence <m>a_k</m> for <m>k \ge s</m> where the terms <m>a_k</m> may depend on <m>n</m>,
      prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^na_k=f(n)</m> for <m>n \ge s</m>.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        We use a combinatorial proof.
        Consider the following situation <ellipsis/>.
      </p>
      <p>
        How many ways are there to <ellipsis/>?
      </p>
      <p>
        First, condition on <m>k=</m>
        (say what <m>k</m> counts).
        In this case, there are
        (show how to get <m>a_k</m>)
        ways to do <ellipsis/>.
        Since cases add <xref ref="thm_cases_add"/>,
        there are a total of <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^na_k</m> ways.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the other hand, (explain how to count using a different method to get <m>f(n)</m>.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Since we counted the same quantity in two different ways,
        it follows that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^na_k=f(n)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      The phrase
      <q>condition on <m>k=</m> (say what <m>k</m> counts)</q>
      indicates that we are considering a list of cases Case <m>s</m>, Case <m>s+1</m>,
      <ellipsis/>, Case <m>n</m> where in Case <m>k</m>,
      there are <m>k</m> of some object.
      Let's see this new proof format in action.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_comb_pf_sum">
      <title>Combinatorial proof of sum</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_comb_pf_sum_row_sum_arith_tri">
            <p>
              Copy the following proof.
              Use a combinatorial proof to prove that
              <me>
                \displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k} =2^n
              </me>
              for any natural number <m>n</m>.
              We made this conjecture about the row sums of the arithmetic triangle in <xref ref="act_pascals_patterns"></xref>
              <xref ref="part_find_row_sum_arith_tri"/>.
              <blockquote>
                <em>Proof.</em>  We use a combinatorial proof.  Consider the following situation: we have the set <m>T = \{1,2,\ldots, n\}</m>.  How many ways are there to choose a subset of <m>T</m>?  First, condition on <m>k=</m> the number of elements in the subset.  There are <m>\binom{n}{k}</m> subsets with <m>k</m> elements for <m>k = 0, 1, 2, \ldots, n</m>. Since cases add <xref ref="thm_cases_add"/>, there are a total of <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k}</m> subsets.  On the other hand, for each element of <m>T</m> we can decide whether it will be in the subset or not (2 choices). There are two choices for whether 1 is in the subset, two choices for whether 2 is in the subset, and so on up to two choices for whether <m>n</m> is in the subset.  Since steps multiply <xref ref="thm_steps_multiply"/>, there are <m>\underbrace{2\cdot 2 \cdots \cdots 2}_{n \text{ times } } = 2^n</m> subsets.  Since we counted the same quantity in two different ways, it follows that
                <me>
                  \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k} =2^n
                </me>.
              </blockquote>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_comb_pf_sum_row_sum_arith_tri"/> to prove that
              <me>
                \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk\binom{n}{k} =n2^{n-1}
              </me>
              for any integer <m>n \ge 1</m>.
              Hints: Out of a group of <m>n</m> people,
              choose a subset to be a committee
              (with at least one person)
              where one of the people on the committee is the chair.
              Condition on <m>k =</m> the number of people on the committee.
              In one way of counting,
              choose the committee members first and then the chair.
              In the other way of counting,
              choose the chair first and then the rest of the committee members.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_special_sums">
    <title>\subspecialsum</title>
    <p>
      We have seen a variety of specific summations that have an explicit formula.
      In this section,
      we look at several common classes of summations that have an explicit formula.
      We begin with an activity.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_special_sums">
      <title>Special sums</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_sum_powers2_to4">
            <p>
              Consider a real number <m>r \neq 1</m> and the sum
              <me>
                S =  \sum_{k=0}^4r^k = 1 + r + r^2 + r^3 + r^4
              </me>.
              Note that <m>S</m> is a function of <m>r</m>.
              Evaluate <m>S</m> when <m>r = 10</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_rminus1_timesS">
            <p>
              Expand <m>(r-1)S</m> and simplify your answer.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_geom_sum_derive">
            <p>
              Use your answer to <xref ref="part_rminus1_timesS"/> to find a formula for <m>S</m> in terms of <m>r</m>.
              Hint: Since <m>r \neq 1</m>,
              you may divide both sides of your equation by <m>r-1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use your formula from <xref ref="part_geom_sum_derive"/> to evaluate <m>S</m> when <m>r=10</m>.
              Check that you get the same answer as in <xref ref="part_sum_powers2_to4"/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_geom_sum_ais1">
            <p>
              Conjecture an explicit formula for
              <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nr^k = 1 + r + r^2 + \ldots + r^n</m> when <m>r \neq 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use your formula from <xref ref="part_geom_sum_ais1"/> to show that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n2^k = 2^{n+1}-1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              In the Handshakes puzzle <xref ref="act_handshakes"/>,
              we saw a formula for the sum of the first <m>n</m> integers,
              <xref ref="thm_hs">namely</xref>, which says
              <me>
                \sum_{k=1}^nk=\frac{n(n+1)}{2}
              </me>.
              Use this formula to evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{10}k</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_sum_sq_formula">
            <p>
              There is an explicit formula for the sum of the first <m>n</m> integers squared, namely
              <me>
                \sum_{k=1}^nk^2=\frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}
              </me>.
              Use this formula to evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{5}k^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Check your answer to <xref ref="part_sum_sq_formula"/> by evaluating <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{5}k^2</m> directly.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Conjecture a formula for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk^3</m> by considering the first few partial sums.
              Hint: Each partial sum is a square.
              What is the pattern in the integers being squared?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Make sure you <xref ref="act_special_sums">complete</xref>
      because we are about to reveal many of the answers.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_finite_geom_sum">
      <title>Finite geometric sum conjecture</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>r \neq 1</m> and the sum
          <me>
            S = \sum_{k=0}^6 ar^k = a + ar + ar^2 + ar^3 + ar^4 + ar^5 + ar^ 6
          </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Note that <m>S</m> is a function of <m>a</m> and <m>r</m>.
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_geom_sum_exam_a3r2">
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>S</m> when <m>a=3</m> and <m>r=2</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We get
                    <me>
                      S = \sum_{k=0}^6 3 \cdot 2^k = 3 + 3 \cdot 2 + 3 \cdot 2^2 + 3 \cdot 2^3 + 3 \cdot 2^4 + 3 \cdot 2^5 + 3 \cdot 2^ 6= 381
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_rminus1_timesS_general">
              <p>
                Expand <m>(r-1)S</m> and simplify your answer.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We get
                    <md>
                      <mrow>(r-1)S  \amp  = (r-1)(a + ar + ar^2 + ar^3 + ar^4 + ar^5 + ar^ 6)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp  = (ar + ar^2 + ar^3 + ar^4 + ar^5 + ar^6 + ar^ 7) - (a + ar + ar^2 + ar^3 + ar^4 + ar^5 + ar^ 6)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp  = \cancel{ar} + \cancel{ar^2} + \cancel{ar^3} + \cancel{ar^4} + \cancel{ar^5} + \cancel{ar^6} + ar^7 - a - \cancel{ar} - \cancel{ar^2} - \cancel{ar^3} - \cancel{ar^4} - \cancel{ar^5} - \cancel{ar^ 6})</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp  = ar^7-a</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp  = a(r^7-1)</mrow>
                    </md>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    Thus, <m>(r-1)S = a(r^7-1)</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_geom_sum_derive_general">
              <p>
                Use your answer to <xref ref="part_rminus1_timesS_general"/> to find a formula for <m>S</m> in terms of <m>a</m> and <m>r</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Since <m>r \neq 1</m>,
                    we can divide each side of the equation by <m>r-1</m> to get <m>\displaystyle S = \frac{a(r^7-1)}{r-1}</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use your formula from <xref ref="part_rminus1_timesS_general"/> to evaluate <m>S</m> when <m>a = 3</m> and <m>r=2</m>.
                Check that you get the same answer as in <xref ref="part_geom_sum_exam_a3r2"/>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We get <m>\displaystyle S = \frac{3(2^7-1)}{2-1}= 3(127) = 381</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_geom_sum_conj_general">
              <p>
                Conjecture an explicit formula for
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nar^k = a + ar + ar^2 + \ldots + ar^n</m> when <m>r \neq 1</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We conjecture that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nar^k = \frac{a(r^7-1)}{r-1} = a\frac{r^7-1}{r-1}</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use your formula from <xref ref="part_geom_sum_conj_general"/> to show that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n4\cdot5^k = 5^{n+1}-1</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We get <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n4\cdot5^k = 4\frac{5^{n+1}-1}{5-1}= \cancel{4}\frac{5^{n+1}-1}{\cancel{4}} = 5^{n+1} - 1</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Let's state the general formula for a geometric sum.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_geom_sum_finite">
      <title>Sum of finite geometric</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>r \neq 1</m>,
          <me>
            \sum_{k=0}^nar^k=a \frac{r^{n+1}-1}{r-1}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Here is an example using the finite geometric sum formula.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_finite_geom_sum">
      <title>Using the finite geometric sum formula</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the finite geometric sum formula <xref ref="thm_geom_sum_finite"/> to evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^7(10\cdot2^k)=10 + 20 + 40 + \ldots + 1280</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Our sum is geometric with <m>a=10</m>, <m>r=2 \neq 1</m>,
          and <m>n=7</m> so by <xref ref="thm_geom_sum_finite"></xref> we have
          <me>
            \sum_{k=0}^710\cdot2^k = 10 \left(\frac{2^{7+1}-1}{2-1}\right) = 10 \left(\frac{2^8-1}{1}\right) = 10(256-1) = \text{ 2,550 }
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      We can use the distributive property <xref ref="defn_integer_algebra_order_operations"/> to derive linearity properties of sums.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_linearity_sums">
      <title>Linearity properties of sums</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>a_k</m> and <m>b_k</m> be sequences of real numbers for <m>k \ge s</m> for some nonnegative integer <m>s</m> and let <m>c</m> be a real number.
          Then
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_constant_times_sum">
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^n(ca_k)=c\sum_{k=s}^na_k</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_sum_of_sum">
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=s}^n(a_k+b_k)=\sum_{k=s}^na_k+\sum_{k=s}^nb_k</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      We have seen the sum of the first <m>n</m> integers, the handshake numbers,
      in many places starting <xref ref="act_handshakes">with</xref>.
      There are also formulas for the sum of the first <m>n</m> squares and cubes.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_sum_formula_polys">
      <title>Summation formulas for powers of integers</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For a nonnegative integer <m>n</m> we have
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_sum_constant">
              <p>
                The sum of a constant: <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n1=n</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_sum_hs">
              <p>
                The sum of the first <m>n</m> integers:
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_sum_squares">
              <p>
                The sum of the first <m>n</m> squares:
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk^2 = \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_sum_cubes">
              <p>
                The sum of the first <m>n</m> cubes:
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk^3 = \left(\frac{n(n+1)}{2}\right)^2</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Here is an example using these formulas.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_sum_formulas">
      <title>Using linearity properties and summation formulas</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use linearity properties and summation formulas to evaluate each sum.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{10}k^2=1 + 4 + 9 + \ldots + 100</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="thm_sum_formula_polys">By</xref>
                    <xref ref="part_sum_squares"/> with <m>n=10</m> we have
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=1}^{10}k^2 = \frac{10(10+1)(2(10)+1)}{6} = \frac{(10)(11)(21)}{6} = 385
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{10}k= 1 + 2 + 3 + \ldots + 10</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="thm_sum_formula_polys">By</xref>
                    <xref ref="part_sum_hs"/> with <m>n=10</m> we have
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=1}^{10}k= \frac{10(10+1)}{2} = \frac{(10)(11)}{2} = 55
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{10}1=\underbrace{1+1+\ldots+1}_{10 \text{ times } }</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="thm_sum_formula_polys">By</xref>
                    <xref ref="part_sum_constant"/> with <m>n=10</m> we have <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{10}1=10</m>.
                    Not sure we really needed a formula here.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{10}(3k+1)(k+2)=(4)(3)+(7)(4)+(10)(5) + \ldots + (31)(12)</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We begin by multiplying
                    (using FOIL)
                    to get <m>(3k+1)(k+2) = 3k^2+5k+2</m>.
                    Then we can apply the linearity properties of sums <xref ref="thm_linearity_sums"/> and our answers from the previous parts to get
                    <md>
                      <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^{10}(3k+1)(k+2) \amp  =\sum_{k=1}^{10} (3k^2+5k+2)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp  = \sum_{k=1}^{10}(3k^2)+\sum_{k=1}^{10}(5k)+\sum_{k=1}^{10}2</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp  = 3\left(\sum_{k=1}^{10}k^2\right)+5\left(\sum_{k=1}^{10}k\right)+2\left(\sum_{k=1}^{10}1\right)</mrow>
                      <mrow>\amp  = 3(385) + 5(55)+2(10) = \text{ 1,450 } </mrow>
                    </md>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_fraction_algebra">
    <title>\subfracalg</title>
    <p>
      Some of our summation formulas involve fractions.
      Let's review fraction arithmetic.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_fraction_addition">
      <title>Adding Fractions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_sum_fractions">
              <p>
                For integers <m>n</m>, <m>m</m>,
                and <m>d</m> with <m>d \neq 0</m>,
                the <term>sum of the fractions</term> is given by
                <me>
                  \displaystyle \frac{n}{d} + \frac{m}{d} = \frac{n+m}{d}
                </me>.
                For example,
                <me>
                  \frac{3}{7} + \frac{2}{7} = \frac{3+2}{7} = \frac{5}{7}
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                To add two fractions using <xref ref="part_sum_fractions"/>,
                we need the two fractions to have the same denominator
                (<term>common denominator</term>).
                If two fractions have different denominators,
                we can replace one or both fractions with equivalent fractions that have a common denominator <xref ref="thm_equal_fractions">using</xref>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Let's practice working with fractions.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="fraction_arithmetic">
      <title>Adding and Subtracting Fractions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In this example,
          we only use computational technology to check our answers.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{3}{4} - \frac{1}{2}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We can use 4 as the common denominator.
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \frac{3}{4} - \frac{1}{2} = \frac{3}{4} - \frac{2(1)}{2(2)} = \frac{3}{4} - \frac{2}{4} = \frac{3-2}{4} = \frac{1}{4}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{3}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We can use <m>(2)(3) = 6</m> as the common denominator.
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{3} = \frac{3(1)}{3(2)} + \frac{2(2)}{2(3)} = \frac{3}{6} + \frac{4}{6} = \frac{3+4}{6} = \frac{7}{6}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{5}{3}-2</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We can rewrite 2 as the fraction
                    <m>\frac{2}{1}</m> and then use 3 as the common denominator.
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \frac{5}{3}-2 = \frac{5}{3}-\frac{2}{1} = \frac{5}{3}-\frac{3(2)}{3(1)} = \frac{5}{3}-\frac{6}{3} = \frac{5-6}{3} = \frac{-1}{3} =^-\frac{1}{3}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{k-1} - \frac{1}{k}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We can use <m>k(k-1)</m> as the common denominator.
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \frac{1}{k-1} - \frac{1}{k} = \frac{k(1)}{k(k-1)} - \frac{(k-1)(1)}{(k-1)(k)} = \frac{k}{k(k-1)} - \frac{k-1}{(k)(k-1)}
                    </me>
                    <me>
                      = \frac{k-(k-1)}{(k)(k-1)} = \frac{k-k+1}{k(k-1)} = \frac{1}{k(k-1)}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    By the way, it is sometimes useful to reverse this equation to write
                    <me>
                      \frac{1}{k(k-1)} = \frac{1}{k-1} - \frac{1}{k}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2^{k-1}} + \frac{1}{2^k}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Recall that <m>2\cdot 2^{k-1} =2^k</m> so we can use <m>2^k</m> as the common denominator.
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \frac{1}{2^{k-1}} + \frac{1}{2^k} = \frac{2(1)}{2(2^{k-1})} + \frac{1}{2^k} = \frac{2}{2^k} + \frac{1}{2^k} = \frac{2+1}{2^k} = \frac{3}{2^k}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{(n-1)!} + \frac{1}{n!}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Recall that <m>n!=n(n-1)!</m> so we can use <m>n!</m> as the common denominator to get
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \frac{1}{(n-1)!} + \frac{1}{n!} = \frac{n(1)}{n(n-1)!)} + \frac{1}{n!} = \frac{n}{n!} + \frac{1}{n!} = \frac{n+1}{n!}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Adding or subtracting fractions is a bit complicated because we need to find a common denominator.
      Luckily, multiplying fractions is simpler.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_multiplying_fractions">
      <title>Multiplying Fractions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For integers <m>n, m, c, d</m> with <m>c,d \neq 0</m>,
                the <term>product</term> of the fractions is given by
                <me>
                  \frac{m}{c} \cdot \frac{n}{d} = \frac{mn}{cd}
                </me>.
                For example,
                <me>
                  \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{7}{5} = \frac{(2)(7)}{(3)(5)} = \frac{14}{15}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Here is an example.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_multiplying_fractions">
      <title>Multiplying Fractions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In this example,
          we only use computational technology to check our answers.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify:
                <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{5}{6}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="defn_multiplying_fractions">By</xref>,
                    <me>
                      \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{5}{6} = \frac{(1)(5)}{(2)(6)} = \frac{5}{12}
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{2}{3}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We have
                    <me>
                      \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{2}{3} = \frac{(1)(2)}{(2)(3)}= \frac{\cancel{2}(1)}{\cancel{2}(3)}=\frac{1}{3}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle 5 \cdot \frac{3}{10}</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    To <xref ref="defn_multiplying_fractions">use</xref>,
                    we need to write 5 as the fraction <m>\frac{5}{1}</m>.
                    Next,
                    <me>
                      5 \cdot \frac{3}{10} = \frac{5}{1} \cdot \frac{3}{10} = \frac{(5)(3)}{(1)(10)} = \frac{\cancel{5}(3)}{\cancel{5}(2)} = \frac{3}{2}
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Simplify <m>\displaystyle 4 \left(\frac{4^m-1}{3}\right)+1</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    First, we can write 4 as <m>\frac{4}{1}</m> and multiply the fractions to get
                    <me>
                      4 \left(\frac{4^m-1}{3}\right)+1 = \frac{4}{1} \left(\frac{4^m-1}{3}\right)+1 = \frac{4\left(4^m-1\right)}{3}+1
                    </me>.
                    Next, we can use 3 as the common denominator and write 1 as <m>\frac{3}{3}</m> to get
                    <me>
                      \frac{4\left(4^m-1\right)}{3}+1 = \frac{4\left(4^m-1\right)}{3}+\frac{3}{3} = \frac{4\left(4^m-1\right)+3}{3}
                    </me>.
                    Next, using the distributive property and simplifying we get
                    <me>
                      \frac{4\left(4^m-1\right)+3}{3} = \frac{4\left(4^m\right)-4(1)+3}{3} =\frac{4\left(4^m\right)-1}{3}
                    </me>.
                    Last, we can simplify the power of 4 to get
                    <me>
                      \frac{4\left(4^m\right)-1}{3} = \frac{4^{m+1}-1}{3}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      It is your turn to practice working with fractions.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_fractions">
      <title>Fractions</title>
      <p>
        On this problem, you may only use technology to check your answers.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{3}{10} - \frac{4}{5}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{3}{10} \cdot \frac{5}{6}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write as one fraction <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{n}+ \frac{1}{n^2}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2^{k-1}} - \frac{1}{2^k}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Write as one fraction and simplify <m>\displaystyle 3 \left(\frac{3^m-1}{2}\right)-1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_sum_proofs_induction">for</xref>
      \subpffsumproofsind</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_odds">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(2k -1)=n^2</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_evens">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{j=1}^n(2j) = n(n+1)</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_factorials">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk(k!) = (n+1)!-1</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
            We saw this sum in <xref ref="act_fact_rep"></xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_geom_sum5">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n4 \cdot 5^k = 5^{n+1}-1</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_prod_1plus_recip">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n \left(1 + \frac{1}{k}\right) = n+1</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_prod_evens">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \prod_{j=1}^n(2j) = 2^nn!</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_proof">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that
            <m>\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^nF_k = F_{n+2}-1</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m> where <m>F_n</m> are the Fibonacci numbers.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_4kplus1">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(4k-1) = n(2n+1)</m> for <m>n\ge 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_recip_powers2">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n\frac{1}{2^k} = 2 - \frac{1}{2^n}</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_sq_proof">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that
            <m>\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^nF_k^2= F_nF_{n+1}</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m> where <m>F_n</m> are the Fibonacci numbers.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_alt_fib_proof">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that
            <m>\displaystyle\sum_{k=1}^n(-1)^{k+1}F_k = 1+(-1)^{n+1}F_{n-1}</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m> where <m>F_n</m> are the Fibonacci numbers.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_multpowers2">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk \cdot 2^k = (n-1)2^{n+1}+2</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_alt_sq">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n(-1)^kk^2 = (-1)^n ~ \frac{n(n+1)}{2}</m> for <m>n\ge 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_squares">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk^2=\frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6}</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
            This exercise <xref ref="thm_sum_formula_polys">proves</xref>
            <xref ref="part_sum_squares"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_squares">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk^3=\left(\frac{n(n+1)}{2}\right)^2</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
            This exercise <xref ref="thm_sum_formula_polys">proves</xref>
            <xref ref="part_sum_cubes"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_poly">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(3k+1)(k+2) = n(n+2)(n+3)</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_frac">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{1}{(2k-1)(2k+1)}=\frac{n}{2n+1}</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_sum_hs_recip">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{2}{k(k+1)}=\frac{2n}{n+1}</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_sum_proofs">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the recursive definitions of partial sums and partial products are?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use proof by mathematical induction to verify the explicit formula of a sum or product?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_math_ind_geom_sum_formula">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use mathematical induction to prove that
          </p>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^nar^k=a\left(\frac{r^{n+1}-1}{r-1}\right)</m> for <m>n \ge 0</m>.
            This exercise <xref ref="thm_geom_sum_finite">proves</xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_comb_sums">for</xref> \subpffcombsums</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_count_cats_dogs">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose there are <m>n</m> cats and <m>n</m> dogs and we want to choose <m>n</m> animals.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If we picked <m>k</m> cats, then how many dogs do we need to choose?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How many ways are there to pick <m>k</m> cats and the rest dogs?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_picked_fav_cat">
                <p>
                  If we picked one favorite animal,
                  how many ways are there to pick the rest?
                  Hint: how many animals are left and how many more do we need?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_comb_pf_sum_binom_sq">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give a combinatorial proof that
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n\binom{n}{k}^2 = \binom{2n}{n}
            </me>
            for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
            Hint: Suppose there are <m>n</m> cats and <m>n</m> dogs and we want to choose <m>n</m> animals.
            Condition on <m>k=</m> the number of cats chosen.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_comb_pf_sum_weighted_binom_sq">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give a combinatorial proof that
            <me>
              \sum_{k=1}^nk\binom{n}{k}^2 = n\binom{2n-1}{n-1}
            </me>
            for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
            Hint: Suppose there are <m>n</m> cats and <m>n</m> dogs and we want to choose <m>n</m> animals including a favorite cat.
            Condition on <m>k=</m> the number of cats chosen.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_comb_pf_sums">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to write a combinatorial proof of a sum?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the phrase
                  <q>condition on <m>k</m></q>
                  indicates?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_comb_pf_sum_hs">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give a combinatorial proof that
            <me>
              \sum_{k=1}^nk = \binom{n+1}{2}
            </me>
            for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
            Hint: How many 2-elements subsets does <m>S = \{0, 1, 2, \ldots,
            n\}</m> have?
            Condition on <m>k =</m> the larger number in the subset.
            Note that the other number in the subset must come from <m>\{0, 1, 2, \ldots,
            k-1\}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_comb_pf_sum_hockey_stick">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give a combinatorial proof
            (<xref ref="pff_comb_proof_sum">using</xref>)
            that
            <me>
              \sum_{k=m}^n \binom{k}{m} = \binom{n+1}{m+1}
            </me>
            for <m>m, n \ge 1</m>.
            Hint: How many <m>(m+1)</m>-element subsets does <m>S = \{0, 1, 2, \ldots,
            n\}</m> have?
            Condition on <m>k =</m> the largest number in the subset.
            Note that the other <m>m</m> numbers in the subset must come from <m>\{0, 1, 2, \ldots,
            k-1\}</m>.
            This proves the hockey stick conjecture from <xref ref="exam_hockey_stick"></xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_comb_pf_factorials">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the set <m>S = \{0, 1, 2, \ldots, n\}</m>.
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_counting_nonid_perms">
                <p>
                  How many nonidentity permutations of <m>S</m> are there?
                  Hint: <m>|S|=n+1</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_counting_perms_that_fix_afterk">
                <p>
                  Consider an integer <m>k</m> with <m>0 \le k \le n</m>.
                  How many permutations of <m>S</m> are there where <m>k</m> is the largest integer that is not fixed?
                  Hint: Such a permutation has the format
                  <me>
                    \sigma = \left(\begin{array}{ccccccccccc} 0 \amp  1 \amp  2 \amp  \cdots \amp  k-1 \amp  k \amp  k+1 \amp  k+2 \amp  \cdots \amp  n-1 \amp  n\\ \underline{~} \amp  \underline{~} \amp  \underline{~} \amp  \cdots \amp   \underline{~} \amp  \underline{~} \amp  k+1 \amp  k+2 \amp   \cdots \amp  n-1 \amp  n \end{array} \right)
                  </me>
                  Since <m>\sigma(k) \neq k</m>,
                  the choices for <m>\sigma(k)</m> are <m>0, 1, 2, \ldots, k-1</m>.
                  That fills in the blank under <m>k</m> and leaves <m>k</m> integers to be arranged into the remaining <m>k</m> blanks.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give a combinatorial proof that <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nk\cdot k! = (n+1)!-1</m> for <m>n \ge 1</m>.
                  Hint: Use part (a) for one count.
                  For the other count,
                  condition on <m>k=</m> the largest integer not fixed by the nonidentity permutation and use part (b).
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_fib_in_pascal">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="act_squares_dominoes">In</xref>,
            we saw that the number of ways to tile a
            <m>1 \times n</m> board using <m>1 \times 1</m> squares and
            <m>1 \times 2</m> dominoes was <m>F_{n+1}</m>,
            where <m>F_n</m> are the Fibonacci numbers.
            In this exercise,
            we use this characterization of the Fibonacci numbers to give a combinatorial proof that
            <me>
              \sum_{k = 0}^n \binom{n-k}{k} = F_{n+1}
            </me>
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_sq_as_fn_dom">
                <p>
                  We want to tile the <m>1 \times n</m> board using <m>s</m> squares and <m>k</m> dominoes.
                  Note that there are <m>k+s</m> tiles.
                  In how many ways can we tile the board?
                  Hint: Think of <m>k+s</m> places to put tiles.
                  Choose which <m>k</m> places will be dominoes.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Let's rewrite the answer to <xref ref="part_sq_as_fn_dom"/> using <m>k</m> and <m>n</m>
                  (instead of <m>s</m>).
                  First, explain why <m>2k+s=n</m>.
                  Next, solve for <m>s</m>.
                  Last, substitute into your answer to <xref ref="part_sq_as_fn_dom"/> to get a count of the number of ways to tile the board using <m>k</m> dominoes in terms of <m>k</m> and <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Count the total number of ways to tile the
                  <m>1 \times n</m> using squares and dominoes by using cases conditioned on <m>k=</m> the number of dominoes.
                  Since cases add <xref ref="thm_cases_add"/>, your answer should be a summation.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_special_sums">for</xref> \subspecialsum</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_eval_sum_formulas_geom">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="thm_geom_sum_finite">Use</xref> to evaluate each sum.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{8}2 \cdot 3^k</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{8}10 \cdot (-1)^k</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_eval_sum_formulas_polys">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="thm_sum_formula_polys">Use</xref> to evaluate each sum.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{8}k</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{8}k^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^{8}k^3</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_using_sum_formulas_polys_lin">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="thm_linearity_sums">Use</xref>
            and <xref ref="thm_sum_formula_polys"></xref>
            to evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(2k+1)(k+3)</m> and write your answer in factored form.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_prod_powersofx">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use summation formulas to simplify each of the following expressions.
            (Yes, each uses summation formulas.)
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>1 + x + x^2 + \ldots + x^n</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>xx^2x^3...x^n</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_special_sums">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the formula is for a finite geometric sum and how to use it?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the linearity properties of sums say?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use the formulas for the sum of the first <m>n</m> integers,
                  their squares, and their cubes?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_perfect">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The integer <m>b</m> is a <term>proper divisor</term>
            of <m>n</m> if <m>b \mid n</m> but <m>b \lt n</m>.
            An integer is <term>perfect</term>
            if it equals the sum of its proper divisors.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Verify that the integer 28 is perfect.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the smallest perfect integer?
                  Justify your answer.
                  That means justify that it's perfect and also that it's smallest.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Can a prime number be perfect?
                  Explain.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_geom_sum_perfect">
                <p>
                  Show how to use the finite geometric sum formula <xref ref="thm_geom_sum_finite"/> to simplify
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^{p-1}2^k</m> where <m>p</m> is a positive integer.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_divisors_power2_times_odd_prime">
                <p>
                  Suppose <m>n = 2^{p-1}q</m> where <m>q</m> is an odd prime.
                  List the divisors of <m>n</m>,
                  using <m>\ldots</m> as needed.
                  Note that <m>2^{p-1}q</m> is the prime factorization of <m>n</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_sum_divisors_perfect">
                <p>
                  Calculate the sum of the divisors of <m>n</m> from <xref ref="part_divisors_power2_times_odd_prime"/> and use your answer from <xref ref="part_geom_sum_perfect"/> to simplify your answer.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Note that <m>n</m> is perfect if the sum of <em>all</em>
                  of the divisors of <m>n</m> is <m>n+n=2n</m>.
                  Suppose <m>p</m> is prime and <m>q=2^p-1</m> also happens to be prime.
                  Observe that <m>q</m> is odd.
                  Consider the integer <m>n = 2^{p-1}q</m> as before.
                  Use <xref ref="part_sum_divisors_perfect"/> to prove that <m>n</m> is perfect.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_infinite_geom_sum">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For readers who have studied calculus,
            an infinite series is defined as a limit.
            For example,
            <me>
              \sum_{k=1}^\infty (ar^k) = \lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n (ar^k)
            </me>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the finite geometric sum formula <xref ref="thm_geom_sum_finite"/> to simplify <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n (ar^k)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If <m>-1\lt r\lt 1</m>,
                  explain why <m>\displaystyle \lim_{n \to \infty} r^{n+1} = 0</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^\infty (ar^k)</m> when <m>-1 \lt r \lt 1</m>.
                  Simplify your answer,
                  including multiplying the top and bottom of the your limit by -1
                  (<xref ref="thm_equal_fractions">using</xref>).
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_fraction_algebra">for</xref>
      \subfracalg</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_add_sub_fractions">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            On this problem,
            do not use computational technology except to check.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Write as one fraction and simplify:
                  <m>\displaystyle \frac{3}{4} + \frac{1}{2}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Write as one fraction and simplify:
                  <m>\displaystyle \frac{3}{4} \cdot \frac{2}{7}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_add_sub_fractions_withn">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Write as one fraction and simplify:
                  <m>\displaystyle \frac{n-1}{2n-1}+\frac{1}{(2n-1)(2n+1)}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Write as one fraction and simplify:
                  <m>\displaystyle \frac{2n-2}{n}+\frac{2}{n(n+1)}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_fraction_arith">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to add and subtract fractions?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why we need a common divisor to add and subtract fractions?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to multiply fractions?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Select Answers and Hints</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_math_ind_sum_odds"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hints: Make sure you use parentheses in <m>f(n-1)=(n-1)^2</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_math_ind_sum_factorials"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: To simplify <m>n!-1+nn!</m>,
        first put the factorials together and factor to get
        <me>
          n!+nn!-1 = (1+n)n!-1
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now, simplify <m>(1+n)n!</m> using <m>(1+n)=(n+1)</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_math_ind_geom_sum5"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: To simplify <m>5^n-1+4\cdot5^n</m>,
        first put the powers of five together and factor to get
        <me>
          5^n+4\cdot5^n-1 = 5^n(1+4)-1 = 5^n\cdot5 - 1
        </me>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_math_ind_prod_1plus_recip"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Note that <m>\displaystyle 1 + \frac{1}{n} = \frac{n}{n} + \frac{1}{n} =\frac{n+1}{n}</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_math_ind_prod_evens"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Note that <m>f(n-1) = 2^{n-1}(n-1)!</m>.
        Simplify <m>\left(2^{n-1}(n-1)!\right)(2n)</m> by collecting the powers of two and separately collecting the factorial.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_proof"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Note that <m>f(n-1) = F_{n+1}-1</m> and that the Fibonacci sequence includes
        <me>
          \ldots, F_n, F_{n+1}, F_{n+2}, \ldots
        </me>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_math_ind_sum_4kplus1"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Use two sets of parentheses to evaluate <m>f(n-1)</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_sq_proof"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hints: Note that
        <me>
          F_{n-1}F_n + F_n^2 = F_n(F_{n-1} + F_n)
        </me>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_math_ind_sum_multpowers2"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Make sure to use parentheses when evaluating <m>f(n-1)</m>.
        Also, note that
        <me>
          n2^n + n2^n = 2n2^n=n(2\cdot2^n)
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          n2^{n+1}-2^{n+1}=(n-1)2^{n+1}
        </me>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_count_cats_dogs"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>n-k</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Step 1 is to pick <m>k</m> out of <m>n</m> cats.
            Step 2 is to pick <m>n-k</m> out of <m>n</m> dogs.
            Steps multiply.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: There are <m>n+n=2n</m> animals to start,
            so after we pick a favorite animal there are <m>2n-1</m> animals remaining.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_comb_pf_sum_binom_sq"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hints: Make sure to choose <m>n</m> animals in total.
        If you choose <m>k</m> cats, then you will need to choose <m>n-k</m> dogs.
        Look <xref ref="thm_sym_arith_triangle">at</xref>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_comb_pf_sum_weighted_binom_sq"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hints: Make sure to choose <m>n</m> animals in total.
        If you choose <m>k</m> cats, then you will need to choose <m>n-k</m> dogs.
        Also, look <xref ref="exer_count_cats_dogs">at</xref>
        <xref ref="part_picked_fav_cat"/>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_eval_sum_formulas_geom"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer is just less than 20,000.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            10
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_eval_sum_formulas_polys"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer is less than 50.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer is just over 200.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer is just under 1,300.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_prod_powersofx"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <xref ref="thm_geom_sum_finite">Use</xref>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Write the product as a single power of <m>x</m> where the exponent is a sum written in sigma notation.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>